@sodle Basically it just detects that there has been an element selected from a display list (i.e. ListTemplate1).  You'll want to use tokens in the list items.  For example:

```def interactive_resp(data):
    if session.attributes["CurrentTree"] == "GroupedAlerts":
        listItems = []
        resDict = session.attributes["resourceDict"]
        for res in resDict:
            listItem = {
                "token":resDict[res],
                "textContent": {
                    "primaryText": {
                        "text":res,
                        "type":"PlainText"
                    }
                }
            }
            listItems.append(listItem)


    enhancedResponse = question("Here are the impacted objects.").list_display_render(template="ListTemplate1", title="Impacted Objects", backButton="VISIBILE", token=None, \
    background_image_url=render_template('backgroundImageURL'), listItems=listItems)

    return enhancedResponse
```
You can see that I'm setting a token for each list item.  You will also want to make sure that you check that you're responding to a Echo Show, using the context.System.device.supportedInterfaces.Display attribute in the request.

```
 if ((session.attributes["CurrentTree"] == "GroupedAlerts") and (context.System.device.supportedInterfaces.Display)):
        enhancedResponse = interactive_resp(outputSpeech)
        return enhancedResponse
```
Once your list is displayed, if the user selects an item from the list you can use display_element_selected to capture that request (and again, this is where tokens come in very handy).

```
@ask.display_element_selected

def element():
    fullResponse = on_element_select(request["token"])
    return fullResponse
```

If anyone is wondering about this, it turns out OrderedDict does not preserve the order of elements specified as kwargs. You have to pass a sequence of pairs explicitly, eg.:
```
thing = OrderedDict(((
    'Address', {
        '#text': 'http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/ws/2004/08/addressing/role/anonymous',
        '@xmlns': 'http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/ws/2004/08/addressing',
    }),  
    ('ReferenceParameters', {      
        'ResourceURI': {    
            '#text': 'http://schemas.dmtf.org/wbem/wscim/1/cim-schema/2/CIM_ComputerSystem',
            '@xmlns': 'http://schemas.dmtf.org/wbem/wsman/1/wsman.xsd',
        },
        '@xmlns': 'http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/ws/2004/08/addressing',
        'SelectorSet': {    
            'Selector': {       
                '#text': 'ManagedSystem',
            },
            '@xmlns': 'http://schemas.dmtf.org/wbem/wsman/1/wsman.xsd',
        },
    },
), ))
```

@foxx I understand it can be annoying, but I think the other option is even worse. For example, with this XML:
```xml
<config>
  <settings>
    <value1>0</value1>
    <value2>false</value2>
  </settings>
  <logging>
    <value3>1</value3>
    <value4>true</value4>
  </logging>
</config>
```

I would expect a `dict` like this:
```python
{
    "config": {
        "settings": {
            "value1": "0",
            "value2": "false"
        },
        "logging": {
            "value3": "1",
            "value4": "true"
        },
    }
}
```

But with your proposal I would get this instead:
```python
{
    "config": [{
        "settings": [{
            "value1": ["0"],
            "value2": ["false"]
        }],
        "logging": [{
            "value3": ["1"],
            "value4": ["true"]
        }],
    }]
}
```

In order to access the configuration values, you would have to use `d['config'][0]['settings'][0]['value1'][0]` instead of `d['config']['settings']['value1']`. Other users might think this is surprising behavior too, so I believe which option is better depends on the use case.

Also, the Python standard library doesn't have a `DefaultDict` that is also an `OrderedDict`. If I followed your suggestion and used `DefaultDict` in the next release, `xmltodict` would lose the elements' ordering information, which could also be surprising for some use cases (and break code that depends on this).

@teqie - you need to move the `with c as draw:` to be outside the two for loops. This is because every time the code inside `with` context comes out of scope, it forces a refresh to the display. The moving it to the top, there is no point in setting the canvas separately, e.g.: 

```python
def drawstuff(array):
    device.contrast(255)
    with canvas(device) as draw:
        for y in range(0,8):
            for x in range(0,8):
                if drawoutput == 1 : print array[y][x],
                draw.point((y,x),fill=array[y][x])
            
        if drawoutput == 1 : print
    if drawoutput == 1 : print
```

_p.s. I would also swap the `x` and `y` variables round_

